  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>[This is a copy of a letter in Ada's hand, no opening or closing]</p>
      <p>Copy I am amused at the facility with which Mr Locke King has persuaded you of his improvement &amp; sincere kindness of heart; considering all that you but too well know of him formerly. There are doubtless many kinds of imperfection of character which materially alter &amp; progress, even after mature years are attained. But a little more general acquaintance with life &amp; with a variety of characters (for your own actual experience has been a limited one), would convince you that the sort of faults he had, are not what ever radically alter, in this life. They may not appear to all people, or under all circumstances; &amp; I only touch that in his intercourse with you, existing causes may not</p>
      <p>occur. As long as this is so, &amp; as you feel no cause to regret your mutual friendliness, I cannot but feel glad of what seems to add to your happiness &amp; to be a true pleasure to you.</p>
      <p>But my opinion of Mr Locke King remains exactly what it was; &amp; I only find that an additional instance has occured (as previously with the G. Kings, &amp; many others), of his consummate skill in the art of bamboozling, &amp; insinuating himself. The motives which exist for the Woburn family to make up to &amp; conciliate you are very strong ones; &amp; such as are worth much pains, &amp; even pecuniary expence. They have made great use of your name, ever since the reconciliation; (a fact they would of course deny,</p>
      <p>or otherwise represent, to yourself).</p>
      <p>Also, the version they give, (&amp; that to persons by no means intimate with them), of the origin of that reconciliation, is rather different from that which you mentioned to me.</p>
      <p>I know some of the parties to whom they volunteered an account of it; that account being that it took place in consequence of a very humble &amp; contrite letter from yourself first, begging pardon for all past offences, &amp; suing for peace.</p>
      <p>As however they give different accounts of any transactions they are interested in, according to the persons they are addressing, it is never very easy to unravel what they do &amp; say; since they are immediately able to get out of any thing they are charged with, by alluding</p>
      <p>to some other case in which they have really acted or spoken differently.</p>
      <p>I fear you, who are yourself simple-minded and confiding, have yet to learn what a maze of double-dealing some are capable of.</p>
      <p>Now I should not have intruded all this on you, for I was well enough pleased with whatever pleased you, to desire by no means unnecessarily to disturb for a moment your own impressions; as long as I did not think you in danger of becoming a dupe yourself; &amp; in short blinded; which one of your last letters certainly does suggest to me.</p>
      <p>It is possible to keep up a courteous intercourse, without however being blind to the nature of the characters.</p>
      <p>You may perhaps recollect</p>
      <p>that in my first (or one of my first) letters to you on this subject, I hinted an uneasiness at the idea of Locke &amp; your husband being much together. This feeling on my part resulted from my knowledge of a case in which they did most mischievously interfere between man &amp; wife. It is not probable that it is their game to do so in your case; at least for some time to come.</p>
      <p>But, should it ever be tehir game, I have such an opinion of their art, that I cannot say what might not possibly ensue.</p>
      <p>At the time I wrote to you some months ago, I certainly had no idea too, of the degree of close intimacy</p>
      <p>that would so suddenly spring up (mushroom-like) between your 2 families.</p>
      <p>That is, if their account of the terms between you is true; for it is from them that my impressions are derived; from what they are saying everywhere, &amp; as publicly as possible. The fact of Locke's having been twice down to you, in so short a time; coupled with your present tone about him, rather inclines me to believe that their representations are not so wholly fabricated or exaggerated as I at first fancied.</p>
      <p>[entire line crossed out] You will probably think that I am your evil genius, always suggesting disagreeable things.</p>
      <p>You have invited it, &amp; if I speak at all, I must ever speak my real opinons.</p>
    </div></body>
